rComments: While he is a respectable professor, he remains a tough grader despite offering various accommodations to his students. This course involves A LOT of reading and is heavily based on memorization and content acquisition. If you are looking for an easy A, I suggest looking for another professor. Nonetheless, you will part will a lot of knowledge.

Overall, he is a good prof. His lectures are a little dry, but he makes jokes to lighten the mood. He focuses a lot on authors and very specific details, so beware of that. He is ready to accommodate his students, which is very helpful.

as everyone said, authors, authors, authors!!!!! i liked haslam, he really wanted students to succeed and would consult us to ensure we got the best grade possible (changing exams to open book, re-structuring grade distribution, etc.). lectures can definitely be dry, but a good prof overall

Worst professor believe me im not exaggerating or being biased. Very lecture heavy and monotone. Way too much material to cover. Makes you buy the textbook he wrote for a 100$. Exam questions are super difficult. Attendance is graded and mandatory. Doesn't accommodate any student problems. Terrible experience...
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', 'Participation matters']

rComments: Great lecturer who knows the course materials pretty well. Always available during office hours and through email. Remembering authors is a MUST to success the course. Grading scheme for essay questions in final is a lil tough (20 points *3)
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Caring', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: He splits the week is split into 1 class and 1 discussion group which sometimes makes it difficult to go through all the material during the lecture. The midterm was all multiple choice but he included questions about authors of the textbook so watch out for that! Grading criteria for the research essay wasn't very clear but the class is ok overall
great prof, can be a hard marker but overall good marker
Content was pretty dull, actually made me consider changing my major. Expectations were unclear for the major essay and just pretty much left me confused.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Graded by few things', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: don't remember much... just had good vibes from him. He has neat America latina knowledge
Avoid this Prof at all cost. Unclear expectations and guidelines.

Fantastic teacher. He posts his powerpoints before class, so you don't have to rush to write everything down. He is not the type to just read off his slides, so you still have to listen and take extra notes. Exam is fair. GO TO THE DISCUSSION GROUPS. About 75% of the exam is stuff is discussed in the DGDs. Super sweet, caring and lovely prof.

The content of the lectures varied, some were boring and some were interesting, he knows what he is talking about and seems dedicated to helping his students. His expectations for the course are clear, and the workload is reasonable.

Paul Haslam is a good prof overall. However, I would say his lectures were dry and boring at times, especially since we had to listen to an oral presentation from a student each time. A lot of people did not listen and the whole atmosphere was just a bit dull. He is also a tough grader.

Mediocre lecturer, but makes it a lot more interesting by bringing in stories from the field. Always prepared for lectures, very clear about expectations for assignments. Midterm was tough but not unreasonable, need to know names of authors from the textbook (which he co-authored). Term paper was interesting, exam was as he described it. Recommend!

Very good prof. Extremely knowledgeable on the course material. The course is very well organized-half the sessions are discussion groups and the readings for them are very interesting. Paul is also super approachable and always willing to help if you're willing to put the effort in.

Great prof, made each lecture interesting with stories from the field. Very down to earth. Pretty funny. You must memorize authors and publications to succeed (just like in real life academia). The course is set up with DGD's.
Such an amazing prof! One of the best  I have ever had! Very nice guy

Professor Haslam is excellent for taking the Introductory course. Having literally written the textbook on the field he is extremely knowledgeable and lectures and explains things very clearly. He is responsive to questions and will give extensive comments on assignments if you ask him to. Marks papers hard though so read his assignments carefully.
Not the most interesting lecturer, but he gets the material across. Make sure you read the textbook, a lot of multiple choice questions on the exam were from the text but not mentioned in class.

Decent prof but his office hours are not very useful nor will he helpfully respond to an email.  Attend the discussion groups, they are the basis for the final exam. If you are not a DVM student, like myself, I do not recommend the course. I see it as a complete waste of an elective.

Great prof. Interesting course content. Enjoyed the format of the course (half lecture / half discussion). Assignments were straight forward and very fair marking. Good balance of take home / in class assignments. I would recommend taking this course!
Very good prof! Interesting material. Structured courses. Alot of material covered. Exams were difficult. Discussion groups were satisfactory.

One of my worst professors so far... hes just SO boring and seriously has a hard time connecting to the class. Hes not engaging or anything. Also the textbook is also uninteresting and in this class we cover so much, but so little so I personally thought I didnt learn ANYTHING. If your a poli Sci student... dont take dvm! (its useless)

One of my favorite teachers ever. He's so smart and his textbook is the perfect compliment to his lectures. his lectures must have improved because I find them to be very interesting. only downside is DGDs, my TA was useless and because of this, DGD questions on the final were hard to answer.

He is an overall average prof. Not absurdly interesting, however he has this ability to discredit students inqueries because he believes that answers are "obvious" and we should "clearly" just know. Reads right off of slides, likes to do "most right" answers.

Paul is very knowledgeable, helpful, and easy to understand. The class required a lot of reading. The midterm was pretty straightforward and easy, yet the class average was 66%. The final exam was exactly how he said it would be and it was pretty easy. I would definitely take another class with Paul. He's an excellent Professor!
He is a fabulous prof! He is very knowledgeable, approachable and communicates expectations well.
Terrible at giving lectures, he seems shy and unable to connect with the class.  He knows the material but needs more practice and input on giving good lectures.

Hopeless lecturer, reads right off the slides, says um a lot and seems to be generally nervous in front of the class.  The class could have been interesting, but he focused too much on the details.  The tutorials repeated exactly what was said in class.  Over half the class failed the mid-term.  Won't take another class with him.  Too boring!

Great prof! Very interested in the subject matter and very knowledgable. The pace of the lectures was too slow sometimes, but they were generally interesting. Always helpful in office hours, and students love him! He has a fanclub group on Facebook, need I say more?

He's a first time prof, so he really tries hard. His lecture notes are very detailed and helpful, but make sure to do all the readings because you will be tested on them. Lots of people complained about the midterm, but I thought it was more than fair. The final was pretty easy too, and the essay topics were really interesting.
Great prof. he made me fall for him as well as for development. go see him during his offices hours. he's adorable
